## Engagement Scoring

```typescript
interface EngagementScores {
  breadth: number;           // Count of activity types (0-10+)
  depth: number;             // Hours per week (0-20+)
  leadership: number;        // 1=none, 2=member, 3=active, 4=leader, 5=exec
  studyIntegration: number;  // Study with others frequency (1-5)
  barrierCount: number;      // Number of barriers selected

  // Composite
  engagementIndex: number;   // 0-100

  // Flags
  underEngaged: boolean;     // breadth=0 AND depth=0
  isolatedStudier: boolean;  // Always studies alone
  hasBarriers: boolean;      // 2+ barriers selected
}

function computeEngagementIndex(scores: EngagementScores): number {
  // Normalize each component
  const breadthScore = Math.min(scores.breadth / 5, 1) * 100;      // Cap at 5 activities
  const depthScore = Math.min(scores.depth / 10, 1) * 100;         // Cap at 10 hrs
  const leadershipScore = ((scores.leadership - 1) / 4) * 100;
  const socialStudyScore = ((scores.studyIntegration - 1) / 4) * 100;
  const barrierPenalty = Math.min(scores.barrierCount * 10, 30);   // Max 30pt penalty

  // Weighted average
  return Math.round(
    breadthScore * 0.25 +
    depthScore * 0.25 +
    leadershipScore * 0.20 +
    socialStudyScore * 0.20 +
    10 -                      // Base points
    barrierPenalty * 0.10     // Barrier deduction
  );
}
```

## Novel Research Questions

Connecting topology to engagement literature:

| Hypothesis | Variables | Expected Finding |
|------------|-----------|------------------|
| H1 | Boundary position â†’ engagement satisfaction | Boundary residents less satisfied with involvement |
| H2 | Shared-class edges â†’ study collaboration | More class connections = more collaborative study |
| H3 | Structural holes â†’ "don't know what's available" | Gap positions correlate with awareness barrier |
| H4 | Bridge residents â†’ leadership roles | Connectors more likely to hold leadership |

**Publication angle:** "Does Position in Residential Social Network Topology Predict Co-Curricular Engagement? A Novel Application of Algebraic Topology to Student Involvement Theory"

